% =============================================================================
\section{User Study}
% =============================================================================

\subsection{Design}

We used a \textbf{within-subjects} design with condition (SLM vs.\ LLM) as
the independent variable, counterbalanced across participants.
Task order was fixed (Writing $\to$ Summarizing $\to$ Planning) to avoid
order effects from task learning; condition order was counterbalanced.
Each participant completed all three tasks in both conditions, yielding
six sessions per participant.
The study was approved by [IRB].

\subsection{Participants}

We recruited [$N$] participants via [recruitment channel].
Inclusion criteria: 18 years or older, self-reported non-expert in
prompt engineering (no prior experience crafting system prompts or
decomposing tasks for AI models).
[Demographics table to be inserted.]

\subsection{Tasks}

The three tasks were drawn from the Reddit formative study:

\textbf{Task~1 -- Writing.}
Participants were asked to produce a short piece of practical writing of
their choice (e.g., an email, a social media post, a short description).
They were instructed to continue until the result was something they would
``realistically use, send, or keep.''
Reference outputs were generated by a human expert and scored with ROUGE-1/2/L
against the final participant output.

\textbf{Task~2 -- Summarizing.}
Participants were given a 250-word passage drawn from a publicly available
news article and asked to produce a summary they could ``use instead of
re-reading the full text.''
Scoring used ROUGE-L and exact-match F1 against a human-written reference
summary.

\textbf{Task~3 -- Planning.}
Participants were given a scenario (e.g., preparing for an exam in five
days with two hours available daily) and asked to produce a day-by-day plan
they judged ``realistic, specific, and easy to follow.''
Scoring used a rule-based pass-rate checklist (coverage of all days,
presence of time estimates, no contradictions).

\subsection{Procedure}

Sessions were conducted remotely over video call.
After a 5-minute onboarding video demonstrating the interface, participants
completed all six task sessions (three tasks $\times$ two conditions) with
the interface open in their browser.
In the SLM condition, the Goal Wizard opened automatically; participants were
encouraged to edit the pre-filled example goal rather than accept it verbatim.
In the LLM condition, participants went directly to chat.
After each session pair (same task, both conditions) participants answered:
(i)~a 7-point forced-choice preference question (\textit{Which output would
you keep?}), (ii)~a 5-point confidence rating, (iii)~a free-text rationale,
and (iv) the 10-item NASA-TLX for workload.
After all six sessions, participants completed a semi-structured exit interview
(15 min) about their scaffolding experience and perceived SLM/LLM trade-offs.

\subsection{Analysis}

Objective metrics (ROUGE, F1, pass rates) were computed automatically.
We used Wilcoxon signed-rank tests for pairwise condition comparisons
(non-parametric; $n <$ 30) with Bonferroni correction for multiple
comparisons across three tasks.
Effect sizes are reported as $r = Z/\sqrt{N}$.
``Good enough'' status (RQ2) was operationalized as: SLM metric score
$\geq$~90\% of LLM score \textit{and} participant preference not
significantly favoring LLM ($p > .05$ by binomial test).
Prompt logs were coded for specificity, constraint completeness, and format
adherence to address RQ3; inter-rater reliability was assessed with Cohen's
$\kappa$.
Exit-interview transcripts were analyzed thematically following Braun and
Clarke~\cite{braun2006thematic}.
